## Beyond the Swift Student Challenge
### Have you shared your app development knowledge with others or used your technology skills to support your community? Describe specific activities and impact. Note: This is about you, not your app. 200 words or less.
In my second year of secondary school, I began developing apps because I wanted to create the apps I used daily myself. Since then, I have been learning from Sugiyama Jōtarō, the winner in both 2020 and 2025. I develop apps alongside peers of the same age who also aspire to be winners, sharing development knowledge, brainstorming ideas, and giving each other feedback.
When I attended the Swift Student Challenge Winners' celebration, I was surprised to see people my own age among the award recipients. I deeply respected the sight of them presenting their work to a large audience. This sparked the thought, ‘Next year, I want to stand in that same place,’ and I became even more dedicated to my app development.
To date, I have created a walking app featuring functionality to record small discoveries during walks through photos and text. I added this feature because I personally enjoy making such discoveries whilst walking.
Moving forward, I wish to develop apps that deliver experiences etched into people's memories. To achieve this, I aspire to become a Swift Student Challenge winner, thereby connecting with diverse individuals and their apps, fostering meaningful exchanges.


